Introduction

New York City’s rat problem has been ongoing for decades, with millions of rats 1 estimated to live in the city. To control the rat population, the city’s health department has been monitoring rat sightings reported by residents over several years until the present day. This report investigates the relationship between rat sightings and temperature in the city int the years 2010-2020, and finds a direct correlation between the two variables. Our findings suggest that interventions targeted at reducing rat populations during warmer months may be effective in addressing the issue.

Background - Overview of the CSVs

The first dataset, which contains information on rat sightings in New York, was obtained from the NYC Open Data Website 2. It provides a comprehensive record of rat sightings over a period of several years. It is probably the most reliable source of information on about rat sightings, but of course it will be missing any unreported sightings and there may be an unusual uptick in the 2020 data during the COVID-19 lockdown as people stayed in their homes, letting trash accumulate outside3.

The second dataset, which contains temperature recordings in New York over the years, was obtained from the National Weather Service 4. We decided to include this dataset because we believe that temperature may be an important environmental factor that can affect rat behavior and population dynamics.

By analyzing these two datasets, we hope to gain insights into how temperature fluctuations and other weather-related factors may influence the frequency and distribution of rat sightings in New York. We will use statistical analysis to identify patterns and correlations in the data.

Discussion

Based on our analysis, we found a strong correlation between temperature and rat sightings in New York City from 2010 to 2020. Specifically, warmer temperatures were associated with an increase in rat sightings. We also noted that the summer months had the highest temperatures and the highest number of rat sightings.

While our findings suggest that interventions targeted at reducing rat populations during warmer months may be effective, we acknowledge that this approach alone may not solve the problem entirely. Other factors, such as population density and access to food, may also play a role in the rat problem.

One limitation of our study is that we only considered temperature as a potential environmental factor. Future studies could explore the impact of other factors, such as humidity and precipitation, on rat behavior and population dynamics. Additionally, our study only analyzed data from 2010 to 2020, and it would be beneficial to analyze data from earlier and later years to determine if there have been any long-term trends in the relationship between temperature and rat sightings. We could also, in the future, measure differences in rat sightings by borough or neighborhood to see if there is an inverse correlation between income levels and the amount of rat sightings.

In conclusion, our analysis indicates that temperature is a significant factor in the frequency and distribution of rat sightings in New York City. However, additional research is needed to fully understand the complex dynamics of the city’s rat population and to develop effective interventions to address the issue.
